Content: Read this sentence from Passage 1.
:box:“The Sun tossed her head with all its yellow hair in d͟i͟s͟d͟a͟i͟n.” (paragraph 6)
What does the word d͟i͟s͟d͟a͟i͟n show about the Sun's attitude toward her mother?

A.Choice: The Sun does not respect her mother.

Key.Rationale: The Sun's actions show disrespect toward her mother.

B.Choice: The Sun thinks her mother is generous.

C.Choice: The Sun is confused by the question her mother asked.

D.Choice: The Sun is nervous because she did not bring her mother anything.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the theme of Passage 1?

A.Choice: High hopes can lead to disappointment.

B.Choice: Listen to those who are older and wiser.

C.Choice: If you are nice to others, they will be nice to you.

Key.Rationale: The Moon is kind to her mother, and her mother rewards her in return.

D.Choice: When planning an event, be sure to include everyone.

Content: Which sentence from the story supports the answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “She would wait for them, she said, and would not set until all three returned and told her about their pleasant visit.” (paragraph 2)

B.Choice: “'What did you bring me from the supper?' she asked.” (paragraph 5)

C.Choice: “She ate it, and then she turned to her three children, for she had something important to say to them.” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “'To those who are thoughtful of their mother, great blessings come.'” (paragraph 9)

Key.Rationale: The mother rewards the Moon for her thoughtfulness.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Why does Fox sing for the sea animals in Passage 2?

Key.Rationale: Fox sings to gain the sea animals' help in getting back to the mainland.

Content: Which sentence supports your answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “As he sang, Fox noticed all kinds of sea creatures swimming in the cold ocean water!” (paragraph 14)

B.Choice: “Then the sea creatures spoke and asked Fox what he was singing.” (paragraph 14)

C.Choice: “He could get the sea animals to aid in his escape.” (paragraph 14)

Key.Rationale: Fox realizes he can use the sea animals to get back to the mainland by singing.

D.Choice: “'Thank you for listening to my song!' Fox said politely.” (paragraph 15)

Content: Select choices before TWO sentences from Passage 2 that show why Eagle gives her eggs to Fox.

:box:	 :MC-A: “I'm warning you, you'd better throw me an egg,” repeated Fox. :MC-B: “If you don't, I'm going to use these sharp blades of grass to cut down your tree!” :MC-C: Because Fox's words frightened Eagle, she threw him an egg. :MC-D: Fox caught the egg in his paw, saying, “Now I want another one!” :MC-E: When Eagle refused, Fox said, “I'll cut down your tree and take all your eggs!” :MC-F: Eagle still felt scared, and so she threw another egg. :MC-G: Now Fox laughed at Eagle, saying, “I tricked you! :MC-H: Do you think it's possible to cut down a tree with some blades of grass?” :MC-I: And he ran away with the two eggs. :MC-J Instead of being frightened, Eagle now was furious! (paragraph 13)

Key.Rationale: This choice shows that Fox scares Eagle twice, which results in Eagle throwing an egg to Fox each time.

Content: Select choices to choose whether each sentence describes Passage 1, Passage 2, or both passages.

Key.Rationale: Passage 1 revolves around the selfish Sun and Wind being punished, while the Moon is rewarded for being unselfish.
Passage 2 focuses on Fox's trickery and how he is rewarded with Eagle's eggs.
In Passage 1, the Moon and Wind eat without saving any for their mother; and in Passage 2, Fox wants Eagle's eggs, which prompts his actions in the story.

Key.Rationale: These paragraphs describe how a flat tire led to the discovery of the fossilized bones.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Why was Susan Hendrickson's discovery exciting for paleontologists?

Key.Rationale: The passage states that skeletons that had been found before Hendrickson's discovery were missing many bones. This explains why her find was impressive.

B.Choice: The Field Museum needed a new display.

C.Choice: No other fossils were found during the trip.

D.Choice: The discovery site had already been searched.

Content: Which sentence supports the answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “While the rest of the team worked to fix the tire, Susan decided to make use of the time.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “Most of the T. rex skeletons that had been found before Hendrickson's discovery were missing many bones.” (paragraph 1)

Key.Rationale: This sentence explains why the discovery was exciting.

C.Choice: “The last-minute discovery was so impressive that Larson even named the dinosaur 'Sue' in honor of Hendrickson.” (paragraph 2)

D.Choice: “Today children from all over the country go to the Field Museumin Chicago, Illinois, to visit Sue.” (paragraph 3)

Content: How is the copy of Sue's skull different from the real one?

Key.Rationale: Scientists created the replica because the real skull was too heavy to display.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the main idea of the passage?

A.Choice: Scientists want to learn more from Tyrannosaurus Sue's skeleton.

B.Choice: Susan Hendrickson accidentally discovered the fossilized bones of a T. rex.

C.Choice: Susan Hendrickson's discovery has allowed scientists to learn a lot about the T. rex.

Key.Rationale: The passage revolves around the impact of Sue Hendrickson's discovery.

D.Choice: Scientists can now study Tyrannosaurus Sue's bones because of how the skeleton is displayed.

Content: Select choices before FOUR sentences from the passage that support your answer in Part A.

:box:	 :MC-A: Paleontologists have learned so much from studying Sue's bones. :MC-B: From the position of her eye sockets, they've learned that Sue had good depth perception. :MC-C: This helped her to be a fierce hunter who could tell how far away her next meal was. :MC-D: From the structure of her ears, they know that Sue and other T. rexes had great hearing, which also helped them to hunt. :MC-E: From the length of her snout, they've discovered that T. rexes had a sharp sense of smell — another quality that gave strength to these giant predators. (paragraph 5)
	 :MC-F: Scientists still have many questions and hope to learn even more from Sue. :MC-G: They would like to figure out whether Sue was male or female, to know whether she was warm- or cold-blooded, and to learn more about her daily activities. :MC-H: Thanks to Susan Hendrickson, Peter Larson, and the rest of the team from the Black Hills Institute, paleontologists all over the world will get the chance to continue to study Sue and try to find some of these answers.

Key.Rationale: This choice reflects the impact that Sue's bones have had on better understanding T. rexes, providing details of the new information scientists gained from studying Sue.
This choice reflects the impact that Sue's bones have had on better understanding T. rexes, providing details of the new information scientists gained from studying Sue.

Content: What are TWO ways that Tyrannosaurus Sue's skeleton is used?

A.Choice: as an interesting Tyrannosaurus rex display that brings visitors into the museum

Key.Rationale: The passage states that children from all over the country come to visit Sue.

B.Choice: as evidence to prove that Tyrannosaurus rexes were warm-blooded creatures

C.Choice: as an example of how to make missing Tyrannosaurus rex bones

D.Choice: as a tool that allows scientists to study Tyrannosaurus rex fossils

Key.Rationale: The passage explains that the skeleton is displayed in such a way that scientists can study the fossils without disrupting the rest of the skeleton.

E.Choice: as a demonstration of the daily activities of Tyrannosaurs rexes

Content: Select choices to show how each image contributes to ideas in the passage.

Key.Rationale: Both images include detailed depictions of Sue's bones and how they are arranged.
The second image shows a much more complete skeleton, including the fake head bones, which is explained in paragraph 3.
This first image only shows Sue's actual head bones, which is supported by information included in paragraph 3.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Why were experts called in to display Sue's skeleton?

A.Choice: The skeleton needed the addition of missing parts.

B.Choice: The skeleton needed to be protected from visitors.

C.Choice: The skeleton needed extra support to hang upright.

D.Choice: The skeleton needed to be arranged in a specific way.

Key.Rationale: The skeleton was arranged so that scientists could study it without disrupting the display.

Content: Select one sentence to support your answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “Most of the T. rex skeletons that had been found before Hendrickson's discovery were missing many bones.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “Today children from all over the country go to the Field Museum in Chicago, Illinois, to visit Sue.” (paragraph 3)

C.Choice: “All of the bones in the display are real — except for the head.” (paragraph 3)

D.Choice: “They designed a way to hang the skeleton so that each individual bone could be removed and studied, then replaced, without disturbing the rest of the display.” (paragraph 4)

Key.Rationale: This sentence shows that the skeleton needed to be arranged in a specific way, to allow scientists to study the bones without disturbing the display.
